nit: this feels a bit like a lack of abstraction, especially since now we have multiple ways of getting the min and max. If a few places we can use the getter methods, but here maybe we could add a higher-level abstraction to the impls, maybe something like
```C++
static bool IsIntendedFor(DepGraphIndex tx_count) noexcept {
    return MIN_INTENDED_TX_COUNT <= tx_count && tx_count <= MAX_TX_COUNT
}
```
or maybe even
```C++
static bool IsIntendedFor(DepGraphIndex tx_count) noexcept {
    return std::clamp(tx_count, MIN_INTENDED_TX_COUNT, MAX_TX_COUNT) == tx_count;
}
```
so that here we're not leaking internals:
```C++
std::unique_ptr<Cluster> TxGraphImpl::CreateEmptyCluster(DepGraphIndex tx_count) noexcept
{
    if (SingletonClusterImpl::IsIntendedFor(tx_count)) return CreateEmptySingletonCluster();
    Assert(GenericClusterImpl::IsIntendedFor(tx_count));
    return CreateEmptyGenericCluster();
}
```

ni2: the format `min <= value && value <= max` may be more intuitive to signal a strict ordering relation

